column6: <o> The troops of King Agamemnon of Mycenae are ready to fight against the troops of Triopas of Thessaly, a battle only avoided when the great warrior Achilles defeats Thessaly's champion in single combat.
<o> Meanwhile, Prince Hector of Troy and his younger brother Paris negotiate a peace treaty with Menelaus, King of Sparta.
<o> Paris, however, is having a secret love affair with Menelaus' wife, Queen Helen, and smuggles her aboard their homebound vessel, enraging Hector.
<o> Upon learning of this, Menelaus meets with Agamemnon, his elder brother, and asks his help in taking Troy.
<o> Agamemnon, who has wanted to conquer Troy for a long time, agrees, since it will give him control of the Aegean Sea.
<o> On King Nestor's advice, Agamemnon has Odysseus, King of Ithaca, persuade Achilles to join them.

<o> In Troy, King Priam is dismayed when Hector and Paris bring Helen, but welcomes her as a guest and decides against sending her home, since Paris will likely follow her and be killed, choosing instead to meet the Greeks in open battle.

<o> The Greeks arrive shortly after and take the Trojan beach, mostly thanks to Achilles and his Myrmidons, among them his cousin Patroclus, who sack the temple of Apollo but allow Hector and the surviving Trojans to return to the city.

<o> Knowing of the coming retribution, Hector leads his wife, Andromache, to a secret tunnel beneath Troy and instructs her to take their child and any survivors she can out of the city should he die and the city fall.
<o> The two fight evenly for a while until Achilles wears Hector down and kills him, dragging his corpse back to the Trojan beach, straining his relationship with Briseis.
<o> Priam, in disguise, sneaks into the camp and meets with Achilles, imploring him to let him take Hector's body back to Troy for a proper funeral.
<o> Ashamed of his actions, Achilles agrees and allows Briseis to return to Troy with Priam, promising a truce of twelve days so that Hector's funeral rites may be held in peace.

column6: <o> King Verence I of Lancre is murdered by his cousin, Duke Felmet, after his ambitious wife persuades him to do so.

<o> The witches hand the child to a troupe of travelling actors, and hide the crown in the props-box.
<o> They acknowledge that destiny will eventually take its course and that the child, Tomjon, will grow up to defeat Duke Felmet and take his rightful place as king.
<o> However, the kingdom is angry about the way the new King is mistreating the land and his subjects.
<o> The witches realise that it will be at least 15 years until Tomjon is able to return and save the kingdom, but by then irreparable damage will have been done.
<o> Granny Weatherwax, with help from the other two witches, manages to cast a spell over the entire kingdom to freeze it in time for 15 years.
<o> Meanwhile, the duke has decided to have a play written and performed that portrays him in a favourable light and the witches in a negative light.
<o> He thinks this will cause the witches to lose their power, and the people will like him.

column3: sex ed: the series[SEP]beloved wife lily
column6: <o> Alder, a village sorcerer from the island of Way, has been tormented by nightmares since the death of his beloved wife Lily.
<o> Every time he falls asleep, he is brought to the wall of stones; the border that divides the world of the living from the dry land of the dead.
<o> He sought guidance on Roke island, where the Master Patterner advised him to travel to the island of Gont and to find Ged.
<o> Ged, the ex-archmage, is powerless but knows more of the world of the dead than any other living man.
<o> Alder finds Ged who now lives in his dead master Ogion's house in Re Albi.
<o> He is alone as his wife Tenar and adopted daughter Tehanu have been summoned to see the king in Havnor.
<o> Ged listens to Alder's tale and bids him to also travel to Havnor to speak to both the king and his family.
<o> King Lebannen is concerned, having made a journey beyond the wall of stones as a young man with Ged, but he has many other worries.
<o> The Kargs, a warlike people from the East who despise sorcery, have demanded that he marry their princess to ensure peace and dragons have been menacing the islands in the West.
<o> Soon after Alder arrives, dragons encroach further east than they have ever been before and the king sails to meet them, with Tehanu in attendance.
<o> Tehanu is present because she has a kinship with dragons, having summoned the great dragon Kalessin as a girl, who referred to her as daughter.
<o> She speaks to a dragon who delivers a cryptic message that the dragons are angry that men have stolen part of their land in the furthest west.

column3: kimi ni todoke (film)[SEP]dragon orm irien arrives shortly[SEP]taking human form
column6: <o> The party return to Havnor, where the dragon Orm Irien arrives shortly after, taking human form to address the king and his council.

<o> The legends of the dragons, the mages and the Kargs are told and compared and it becomes clear that the cycle of death, life and rebirth have been disrupted and that the true natures of both men and dragons are being threatened.
<o> The party decide to sail to Roke, the centre of the world, to find a resolution.
<o> After arrival, they are re-united with the Masters who run the great school of Mages.
<o> They gather, and the men, women, mages and dragons travel together to the wall of stones where the dead are attempting to tear it down.
<o> With reality weakening, they come to realize that the world is in an unnatural state.
<o> Dragons and men were the same once, but dragons chose a life of freedom and immortality in the furthest west, while men chose a life of mastery, power and rebirth.

<o> However, the ancient mages cast spells that stole some of the west from the dragons for men to go to after death, little knowing that instead of eternal life, their acts had created a grey, windless and lifeless place for their souls to linger.
<o> Tehanu and Alder start to tear down the wall, assisted by both the others and the dead and the border is broken.
<o> Tehanu takes her true form as a dragon, Alder is briefly re-united with his wife before his death, and the dead are freed from the dry land, which returns to life and reclaimed by the dragons.
<o> As the rightful balance of the world is restored, the king marries the Kargish princess whom he has come to love and admire and Tenar returns to Gont and to Ged.

column6: <o> Rincewind and Twoflower are then taken by the Krullians to their capital, where they learn that the Krullians intend to discover the sex of Great A'Tuin by launching a space capsule over the edge of the Disc, and plan to sacrifice Rincewind and Twoflower to get the god Fate to smile on the voyage, Fate insisting on their sacrifice after they caused him to lose the earlier game.
<o> Rincewind and Twoflower attempt to escape, but end up stealing the capsule, which is launched with Twoflower inside, the tourist wishing to see the other worlds of the universe.
<o> Rincewind is unable to get into the capsule in time, and falls off the Disc alongside it, the Luggage following them soon after.
<o> The story segues immediately into the beginning of The Light Fantastic; the two books can therefore be seen as one two-volume novel.
<o> The book begins shortly after the ending of The Colour of Magic, with wizard Rincewind, Twoflower and the Luggage falling from the Discworld.

<o> They are saved when the Octavo, the most powerful book of magic on the Discworld, readjusts reality to prevent the loss of one of its eight spells, which has resided in Rincewind's head since his expulsion from Unseen University: Rincewind, Twoflower and the Luggage end up in the Forest of Skund.
<o> Meanwhile, the wizards of Ankh-Morpork use the Rite of Ashk-Ente to summon Death in order to find an explanation for the Octavo's actions.

<o> The next morning, offended by Mick's assertion that as a "sheila" (Aussie slang for a female) she is incapable of surviving the Outback alone, Sue goes out alone to prove him wrong but takes his rifle with her at his request.

column6: <o> The first half of the book, titled "The General", tells how the experienced General Bel Riose of the Galactic Empire launches an attack against the Foundation.
<o> The Empire still retains far more resources and personnel than the Foundation and Riose is willing to use that advantage to its fullest.

<o> Lathan Devers, a native of the Foundation, and Ducem Barr, a fugitive from the planet Siwenna, intercept a message that summarizes the General's doings, and escape to Trantor, to see Emperor Cleon II and show him the message.
<o> In their attempts to contact the emperor, Devers and Barr attract the attention of Trantor law enforcement and are forced to flee the planet.
<o> In the end, the emperor decides that Riose is a threat to his status and to the balance of the Empire and recalls him to Trantor.

<o> The story follows a plot by a secret brotherhood, the Unique and Supreme Lodge of the Elucidated Brethren of the Ebon Night, to overthrow the Patrician of Ankh-Morpork and install a puppet king, under the control of the Supreme Grand Master.
<o> Using a stolen magic book, they summon a dragon to strike fear into the people of Ankh-Morpork.
<o> Once a suitable state of terror and panic has been created, the Supreme Grand Master proposes to put forth an "heir" to the throne, who will slay the dragon and rid the city of tyranny.

column3: a chinese ghost story ii[SEP]bells without accomplishing anything[SEP]walk around ringing
column6: <o> The Watch is generally regarded as a bunch of incompetents who walk around ringing their bells without accomplishing anything, which is largely accurate.
<o> Carrot's arrival changes this; Whereas the existing officers are either cynical, incompetent, mildly crooked or all three, Carrot is honest, straightforward and idealistic.

<o> Having memorized the Laws and Ordinances of the Cities of Ankh and Morpork, on his first day he tries to arrest the head of the Thieves' Guild for theft (the Thieves' Guild is permitted a quota of legally licensed thieving, a concept that the book of ancient Laws does not take into account).

<o> Brought up as a dwarf, a literal, dutiful people, his absolute dedication and conscientiousness unnerves his colleagues who view it as bordering on the suicidal in the face of the reality of Ankh-Morpork life.
<o> Carrot's policing style is reminiscent of traditional idealized portrayals of British police, such as Dixon of Dock Green, but astoundingly, it actually seems to work.
<o> Carrot's enthusiasm strikes a chord with Vimes, who decides that the Watch should try to carry out its ostensible duties.

<o> Its privileged HQ is Griboyedov's House and is made up of corrupt social climbers and their women (wives and mistresses alike), bureaucrats, profiteers, and, more generally, skeptical unbelievers in the human spirit.
<o> The second setting is the Jerusalem of Pontius Pilate, described by Woland in his conversations with Berlioz and later echoed in the pages of the Master's novel.

<o> This part of the novel concerns Pontius Pilate's trial of Yeshua Ha-Notsri, his recognition of an affinity with, and spiritual need for, Yeshua and his reluctant but resigned submission to Yeshua's execution.

<o> Part one of the novel opens with a direct confrontation between the unbelieving head of the literary bureaucracy, Berlioz, and an urbane foreign gentleman (Woland) who defends belief and reveals his prophetic powers.
<o> Berlioz brushes off the prophecy of his death, only to have it come true just pages later in the novel.

<o> Major episodes in the first part of the novel include a satirical portrait of the Massolit and their Griboyedov house; Satan's magic show at the Variety Theatre, satirizing the vanity, greed and gullibility of the new rich; and Woland and his retinue capturing the late Berlioz's apartment for their own use.
<o> Part two of the novel introduces Margarita, the Master's mistress, who refuses to despair over her lover or his work.
<o> She is invited to the Devil's midnight ball, where Woland offers her the chance to become a witch with supernatural powers.

<o> This takes place the night of Good Friday, with the same spring full moon as when Christ's fate is sealed by Pontius Pilate and he is crucified in Jerusalem, which is also dealt with in the Master's novel.

<o> In the Netherlands of the 1920s, Dreverhaven (Decleir), a dreaded bailiff, is found dead, with a knife sticking out of his stomach.

column3: the accident man[SEP]jacob willem katadreuffe[SEP]ambitious young lawyer[SEP]van huãªt ),
column6: <o> The obvious suspect is Jacob Willem Katadreuffe (Van HuÃªt), an ambitious young lawyer who worked his way up from poverty, always managing to overcome Dreverhaven's personal attacks against him.
<o> He is arrested and taken to police headquarters, where he reflects back on the story of his long relationship with Dreverhaven, who, police learn, is also Katadreuffe's father.
<o> The story begins when Katadreuffe's taciturn mother, Joba (played by Schuurman), worked as a housekeeper for Dreverhaven.
<o> During that time, they had sex only once (it is implied that the encounter was forced upon Joba).
<o> She becomes pregnant and leaves her employer to make a living for herself and her son.
<o> Even as a child, Katadreuffe finds that his path crosses with Dreverhaven, often with dire consequences.
<o> When he is arrested for becoming involved in a boyish theft and tells the police that Dreverhaven is his father, Dreverhaven refuses to recognize him as his son.
<o> When, as a young man, he unwittingly takes a loan from a bank that Dreverhaven owns to purchase a failed cigar store, Dreverhaven sues him to win the money back and force him into bankruptcy.

column3: hell on wheels (episode)[SEP]katadreuffe manages[SEP]law firm retained
column6: <o> Still, Katadreuffe manages to pay back the debt, finding a clerical position in the law firm retained to pursue him for his cigar-store debt.

<o> He manages to secure this job, even though most of his education is derived from reading an incomplete English-language encyclopedia that he finds as a boy in his mother's apartment; studying this set, he manages to teach himself English, which turns out to be a valuable talent in the eyes of his employers.

<o> After paying back the cigar-store debt, Katadreuffe immediately seeks a second loan from Dreverhaven, so that he can finance his education and legal studies and, ultimately, take and pass the bar examination.
<o> Dreverhaven agrees, on the condition that he can call back the loan at any time.
<o> Despite the bailiff's efforts to hinder his son, Katadreuffe passes his bar examination and qualifies as a lawyer.

<o> On the afternoon when his firm holds a celebration of his becoming a lawyer (the day with which the film begins, the day of the murder), Katadreuffe storms into Dreverhaven's office to confront his lifelong tormentor, the bailiff.

<o> Lee goes on to capture Philadelphia, earning the Confederate States of America diplomatic recognition from both the United Kingdom and France, thus winning the war (which is known as the War of Secession in the alternate timeline) and independence from the United States on November 4, 1862.

<o> He grasps the hands of a girl (Shayla Mackarvich) who is inexplicably under the water with him and an instant connection forms between the two.
<o> Allen can now breathe under water as he is in the hands of a mermaid.
<o> However, Allen is pulled to the surface by the deck hands and the two are separated, though apparently no one else sees the girl.

<o> Allen comes to believe the encounter was a near-death hallucination, but his bond with the mermaid proves so strong that his subsequent relationships with women fail as he seeks the connection he felt with the mermaid.

column3: making the cut: guards conversion course[SEP]treasured life
column6: <o> A curious twist is introduced here; whereas the name "Ransom" is said to be derived from the title "Ranolf's Son", it can also refer to a reward given in exchange for a treasured life.
<o> Recalling this, and recalling that his God would (and has) sacrificed Himself in a similar situation, Ransom decides to confront the Tempter outright.
<o> Weston's body is unable to withstand this despite the Tempter's superior abilities of rhetoric, and so the Tempter flees.
<o> Ultimately Ransom chases him over the ocean, Weston fleeing and Ransom chasing on the backs of giant and friendly fish.

<o> During a fleeting truce, the 'real' Weston appears to momentarily re-inhabit his body, and recount his experience of Hell, wherein the damned soul is not consigned to pain or fire, as supposed by popular eschatology, but is absorbed into the Devil, losing all independent existence.

<o> Ransom meets the King and Queen together with the OyÃ©resu of Mars and Venus, the latter of whom transfers its divinely ordained dominion over the planet to the King and Queen.
<o> All the characters celebrate the prevention of a second biblical "Fall" and the beginning of a utopian paradise in this new world.
<o> The Great Dance is the exchange of higher and lower things, as when an advisor gives power to a royal child.
<o> The Great Dance is suggested to be the essential truth of life in the Solar System, and possibly of the nature of God, and alludes to the journey of Dante in the Divine Comedy.

<o> Ransom's mission on Venus accomplished, he returns, rather reluctantly, to Earth in the same manner in which he made the outward journey; his new mission is to continue the fight against the forces of evil on their own territory.

<o> The only way to prevent this catastrophe is to prevent the god from awakening.

column6: <o> One day, as Neville is in a department store helping himself to new clothing, he spots a woman who quickly runs away.
<o> He pursues her outside but later decides he is hallucinating and dismisses the sighting.
<o> After a summary trial he is found guilty of heresy by the family's leader, Jonathan Matthias, a former news anchorman.
<o> Neville is sentenced to death and nearly burned at the stake in Dodger Stadium.
<o> He is rescued by Lisa, the woman he had earlier dismissed as a hallucination, and Dutch, a former medical student.
<o> Lisa and Dutch are part of a group of survivors, some of whom are children.
<o> Although their youth has given them some resistance to the disease, they are still vulnerable to it and will eventually succumb to mutation.

<o> The life of Vernon Little, a normal teenager who lives in Martirio, Texas, falls apart when his best friend, Jesus Navarro, murders their classmates in the schoolyard before killing himself, and Vernon is taken in for questioning.
<o> He cooperates with Deputy Vain Gurie, because he had been running an errand for a teacher, mr Nuckles, and is not involved in the massacre.

<o> The perception of Vernon's innocence weakens when his Mom's best friend, the food-obsessed Palmyra (Pam) arrives and, against Vernon's better judgment, whisks him off to Bar-B-Chew Barn, allowing the police to claim he is a flight risk.
<o> Eulalio ("Lally") Ledesma, supposedly a CNN reporter, ingratiates himself to Doris, Vernon's Mom, and promises to help Vernon "shift the paradigm" of his story.
<o> When the court-appointed shrink, dr Goosens, touches him inappropriately, Vernon leaves, knowing it can wreck hopes for bail.

column3: i am frigid... why?[SEP]bail hearing suggests
column6: <o> Vernon's bail hearing suggests a possible alibi and no grounds for holding him, so Vernon is released as Goosens' outpatient, subject to regular sessions.

<o> Vernon, however, is intent on living out the movie Against All Odds, repelled by Lally not only betraying him again with a video interview with Nuckles, but also by insinuating himself into Vernon's family life - including sharing Mom's bedroom.
<o> Learning a posse intends to search Keeter's field, where his rifle is hidden, Vernon races to beat them, but meets a stranger who reveals Lally is a fraud.
<o> Vernon confirms it by phoning Lally's blind, neglected mother, and plans how to get her to talk with Mom.

column6: <o> Unfortunately, Earth's only ground spaceport gets taken over by the demons, who place a flame barrier over it, preventing any ships from leaving.
<o> The marine then battles hordes of demons and is able to deactivate the force field, allowing the remaining humans to escape.
<o> Once all the survivors escape Earth, the marine is the only human left on the planet.

<o> Just as he sits down to await death, knowing that he saved mankind, the marine then receives an off-planet transmission from the survivors in orbit, who have managed to find out where the armies of Hell are coming from.
<o> The message reveals that the demonic base is in the center of the marine's own hometown.
<o> He then fights through the city until he reaches the base, but sees there is no way to stop the invasion on that side.
<o> He then decides to step into the portal to try deactivating it from the other side, entering Hell (a different Hell than the one that the Deimos moon floats over in the first Doom).
<o> After fighting through the hordes of Hell, the marine reaches the location of the biggest demon he has ever seen, called the Icon of Sin (Baphomet).
<o> Its death causes devastation on Hell, and the portal to Earth has been sealed.
<o> Now with Hell defeated, the marine joins with the other humans in an effort to rebuild and restore life on Earth.
<o> A message, carried by pointless albatross, arrives for Lord Vetinari from the Agatean Empire.

<o> The message explains that the Silver Horde (a group of aged barbarians introduced in Interesting Times, wherein they conquered the Empire, and led by Cohen the Barbarian, now the Emperor) have set out on a quest.

<o> The first hero of the Discworld, "Fingers" Mazda, stole fire from the gods and gave it to mankind (analogous to Prometheus), and was chained to a rock to be torn open daily by a giant eagle as punishment.

column6: <o> As punishment for creating The Kite (which allowed humans to travel higher than the gods) and for not expressing belief in the gods, Leonard is ordered by the gods to paint the entire ceiling of the Temple of Small Gods with a spectacular mural of the whole world (despite Blind Io saying he would be satisfied with "a nice duck-egg blue with a few stars").
<o> They impose a time limit of 10 years on the taskâ€”unassisted, "even with the scaffolding".
<o> (Leonard finishes the task in a few weeks) Carrot asks for a boon to allow for the repairs of The Kite so that they can return to Ankh-Morpork.

<o> Rincewind asks for a blue balloon and the Librarian asks for some library supplies (and a red balloon) and manages to refrain from bouncing Blind Io's head on the ground after Io calls him 'a monkey'.
<o> Valkyries come to take the heroes to the Halls of the Slain, where a feast has been prepared for them.
<o> Instead, the Silver Horde, refusing to accept their deaths, steal the valkyries' horses and set off to find other worlds to "do heroic stuff in".
<o> Death does not appear to them, as he often does when Discworld characters die, although he subsequently appears to Vena, and is evasive about whether he is "collecting".

<o> After the Horde leave with the Valkyries' horses, their first stop is to visit Mazda where he is being punished, cut off his chains, give him something to drink, and leave him a sword so that he may deal with his punisher.
<o> The bard, changed by his experience, composes a new style of saga, one with musical accompaniment, about it.

<o> After the ship encountered a meteor field and was disabled, he ordered the human crew to return to Earth, but Kate's father chose to remain aboard and has since died.
<o> Reinhardt then reveals that he has spent the past 20 years studying the black hole and intends to fly the Cygnus through it.
<o> Only Durant believes it is possible and asks to accompany Reinhardt on the trip.

<o> The rest of the Palomino crew grow suspicious of the faceless drones' human-like behavior: Booth sees a robot limping and Holland witnesses a robot funeral and discovers the Cygnus crew's personal items in the ship's living quarters.

<o> When Kate tells Durant, he removes the reflective faceplate from a "drone" to reveal the zombie-like face of a crew member.

column6: <o> In the program, an experimental and potentially lethal gas called terrazine is used to enhance the genetic structure of the Dominion's psychic ghost agents.
<o> The process is described as changing the agents into "shadowy superhuman beings bent on executing the will of their true master".
<o> It is into the midst of this that Nova finishes her training and is dispatched in operations against the Koprulu Liberation Front, a rebel group that challenges Mengsk's empire.
<o> This revelation causes her to question her loyalty to the Dominion and could upset the balance of power within the galaxy.

column6: <o> The senior crew discuss their latest mission: to make contact with the Tamarian race who have been transmitting signals toward Federation space for weeks.
<o> The Enterprise makes contact with a Tamarian ship in orbit around the planet El-Adrel.

<o> Though the universal translator can translate their words, the Tamarians communicate only through allegory, which baffles the Enterprise crew because they do not know the stories to which the Tamarians are referring.
<o> Frustrated by their failure at communication, the Tamarian captain, Dathon, has himself and Captain Picard transported to the planet's surface.
<o> The Tamarians then create a scattering field in the planetary atmosphere to prevent transport functions from being used on either captain.

column3: war witch[SEP]incredible ancient prophecies involving[SEP]bantam edition boldly suggested
column6: <o> Cover art on the Bantam edition boldly suggested that the 1970s were the "era of the Antichrist as foretold by Moses and Jesus," and called the book "a penetrating look at incredible ancient prophecies involving this generation".

<o> Descriptions of alleged "fulfilled" prophecy were offered as proof of the infallibility of God's Word, and evidence that "unfulfilled" prophecies would soon find their denouement in God's plan for the planet.
<o> He cited an increase in the frequency of famines, wars and earthquakes, as key events leading up to the end of the world.

column3: special project[SEP]european economic community[SEP]lindsey also predicted[SEP]revived roman empire
column6: <o> Lindsey also predicted that the European Economic Community, which preceded the European Union, was destined (according to Biblical prophecy) to become a "United States of Europe", which in turn he says is destined to become a "Revived Roman Empire" ruled by the Antichrist.

<o> Lindsey wrote that he had concluded, since there was no apparent mention of America in the books of Daniel or Revelation, that America would not be a major player on the geopolitical stage by the time the tribulations of the end times arrived.
<o> He found little in the Bible that could represent America, but he suggested that could be speaking of America in part.

<o> Although Lindsey did not claim to know the dates of future events with any certainty, he suggested that indicated that Jesus' return might be within "one generation" of the rebirth of the state of Israel, and the rebuilding of the Jewish Temple, and Lindsey asserted that "in the Bible" one generation is forty years.
<o> Some readers took this as an indication that the Tribulation or the Rapture would occur no later than 1988.
<o> In his 1980 work The 1980s: Countdown to Armageddon, Lindsey predicted that "the decade of the 1980s could very well be the last decade of history as we know it".
<o> The novel is told from the point of view of Gilgamesh, and is primarily ambivalent about the supernatural elements of the epic.
<o> Gilgamesh is a giant among men and an amazing warrior, even since he was very young.
<o> When the king of Uruk (his father) dies, Gilgamesh is exiled by the recently crowned Dumuzi, jealous of his skills and power.
<o> When in time Dumuzi dies, Gilgamesh comes back to the kingdom to be proclaimed.

column6: <o> When the raiders' ship abandons Kari and Olvir, it becomes apparent that the spaceship is actually a transport carrying Lazars, sufferers of a leprosy-like disease, to a space station named Terminus.
<o> The station is owned by Terminus, Inc, which claims that a cure exists there, but no-one has returned from it.
<o> Nyssa, separated from the Doctor, is infected by the disease and ushered away with the rest of the Lazars.
<o> They are slave labour, kept alive only by regular doses of a drug called "hydromel", which is supplied by the corporation.
<o> The Doctor discovers that Terminus is at the centre of the known universe and finds this information unsettling.
<o> Nyssa, meanwhile, is given over to the Garm, a giant dog-like biped, who takes her to a chamber and exposes her to radiation.
<o> The Doctor and Kari find the control room of Terminus and he realizes that Terminus is also a time ship.

<o> If he chooses the door with the lady behind it, he is innocent and must immediately marry her, but if he chooses the door with the tiger behind it, he is deemed guilty and is immediately devoured by it.
<o> The king learns that his daughter has a lover, a handsome and brave youth who is of lower status than the princess, and has him imprisoned to await trial.
<o> By the time that day comes, the princess has used her influence to learn the positions of the lady and the tiger behind the two doors.

<o> Instead, the narrator departs from the story to summarize the princess's state of mind and her thoughts about directing the accused to one fate or the other, as she will lose him to either death or marriage.

<o> At the beginning of this story, it is made quite clear that Dorothy Gale (the primary protagonist of many of the previous Oz books), is in the habit of freely speaking of her many adventures in the Land of Oz to her only living relatives, her Aunt Em and Uncle Henry.
<o> Neither of them believes a word of her stories, but consider her a dreamer, as her dead mother had been.

<o> She is undeterred (unlike her alter ego in the film Return to Oz who is much perturbed by her guardians' doubts) Later, it is revealed that the destruction of their farmhouse by the tornado back in The Wonderful Wizard of Oz has left Uncle Henry in terrible debt.
<o> In order to pay it, he has taken out a mortgage on his farm.
<o> If he cannot repay his creditors, they will seize the farm, thus leaving Henry and his family homeless.
<o> He is not too afraid for himself, but both he and his wife, Aunt Em, fear very much for their niece's future.

<o> The Masters, whom the Mediators obey, have also concealed the existence of one Motie subspecies from the humans: Warriors more deadly than any human, even Sauron supersoldiers.

column6: <o> Her mother's theory that a wife must support her husband in his career comes into play when the author marries a friend of her brother ("Bob") who soon admits that his dream is to leave his current office job and start a chicken ranch.
<o> Knowing nothing about ranching, but eager to support her husband, the author encourages the dream but is unprepared for the primitive conditions that exist on the ranch he purchases.

<o> From this "set up" the book turns to anecdotal stories that rely upon the proverbial "fish out of water" tales that pit MacDonald against her situation and her surroundings, such as the struggle to keep up with the need for water, which needs to be hand carried from a pond to the house until a tank is installed or keeping a fire going in "Stove" or the constant care that chicks need.

<o> At one point a guest expresses envy of MacDonald and her husband, as she thinks they live a life full of fresh air and beautiful scenery, which is then followed by MacDonald pointing out that while the guest had lounged in bed that morning, she and her husband had been up before sunrise working for several hours, and then again the couple had stayed up long into the night after the guest had gone to bed.

column6: <o> Fisher remembers pursuing an elusive killer called the "Lotto Murderer", who was strangling and then mutilating young girls who were selling lottery tickets.
<o> He attempts to track down the killer using the controversial methods outlined in a book entitled The Element of Crime, written by his disgraced mentor, Osborne.
<o> He is joined in his search by a prostitute named Kim, who, it turns out, has had a child by his target.

<o> Fisher's search is based on a tailing report written by Osborne when trying to track down a murderer who had been killing in the same way as the "Lotto Murderer", but who, supposedly, has since died in a crash.
<o> The Osborne method requires the detective to try to identify with the mind of the killer.
<o> This he does, but, in so doing, begins to behave more and more like a serial killer himself.

<o> On the third day, when the girl has been taken to an even larger room filled with straw and told by the king that he will marry her if she can fill this room with gold or execute her if she cannot, the girl has nothing left with which to pay the strange creature.
<o> He extracts from her a promise that she will give him her firstborn child and so he spins the straw into gold a final time.

column3: chinna thambi periya thambi[SEP]eternal champion gathers
column6: <o> Seeking to restore balance to the world, the Eternal Champion gathers these souls from time moments before their deaths to participate in a fighting tournament.
<o> The victor will be able to change their fate and bring balance to the universe, whilst the losers will be forced to live out their deaths just as history intended.
<o> Unlike most fighting games, or video games in general, there are no characters in this game that are "bad" or "evil".
<o> Each character has been chosen because they are either inherently good, or they have the potential to do great good and change the course of history for the better.

<o> The story begins with Aylward (Ingrid Bergman) being rejected as a potential missionary to China because of her lack of education.
<o> dr Robinson (Moultrie Kelsall), the senior missionary, feels sorry for her and secures her a position in the home of a veteran explorer with contacts in China.
<o> Over the next few months, Aylward saves her money to purchase a ticket on the Trans-Siberian railway, choosing the more dangerous overland route to the East because it is less expensive.
<o> Once in China, she settles in the town of Yang Cheng, where she secures a post as assistant to a veteran missionary, Jeannie Lawson (Athene Seyler).
<o> Lawson has set up an inn for traveling merchants, where they can get a hot meal and hear stories from the Bible.
<o> The film follows Aylward's acculturation, culminating in her taking over the inn when Lawson dies in an accident.

<o> The local Mandarin (Robert Donat) appoints Aylward, a stubborn but endearing woman, as his Foot Inspector to ensure that the ancient practice of foot binding is eradicated in the region he governs.
<o> She succeeds in this, and manages to put down a prison revolt as well, winning her the esteem of the local population and of the Mandarin.
<o> Meanwhile, however, China is being invaded by Japan, and Aylward is encouraged by Lin (Curt JÃ¼rgens) to leave.
<o> She refuses, and as the town of Yang Cheng comes under attack, she finds that she has fifty orphans in her care.

column3: mini and franky[SEP]religious conviction ).[SEP]rather taken aback

<o> She is now left alone with the children, aided by Li (Burt Kwouk), the former leader of the prison revolt she helped to resolve.

<o> Lin tells her that the only hope for safety is to take the children to the next province, where trucks will evacuate them to a safer area, but they must get there within three weeks, or the trucks will leave without them.

<o> Although it should only have taken them a week, the roads are infested with Japanese patrols, and the group has to cut across the mountains.
<o> After a long, difficult journey, they all arrive safely (except for Li, who died to save them from a Japanese patrol) on the day the trucks are to leave.
<o> Aylward is greeted by dr Robinson, and she reminds him of how he rejected her as a missionary years before.
<o> The film culminates with the column of children, led by Aylward, marching into the town, singing the song "This Old Man" to keep up their spirits.

column6: <o> (The term "count zero interrupt" or CZI could be found in the book Programming the Z80 by Rodnay Zaks) As with Neuromancer and later Gibson works, there are multiple story-line threads which eventually intertwine: Thread One: In the southwestern USA, Turner, a corporate mercenary soldier, has been hired by former partner Conroy to help Christopher Mitchell, a brilliant researcher and bio-hacker, make an illegal career move from Maas' corporate fortress built into a mesa in the Arizona desert to Hosaka, a rival corporation.
<o> The attempt is a disaster, and Turner ends up escaping with the scientist's young daughter, Angie Mitchell instead.
<o> She carries the plans, implanted in her brain by her father, of the secrets of construction of the extremely valuable "biosoft" that has made Maas so influential and powerful.

column3: mondomanila (novel)[SEP]something resembling omniscience[SEP]multibillionaire josef virek[SEP]see thread three
column6: <o> This "biosoft" is what multibillionaire Josef Virek (see thread three) desires above all else, so that he can make an evolutionary jump to something resembling omniscience and immortality.
<o> During their flight from both Maas and Hosaka agents, Turner and Angie stay with Rudy, the former's estranged brother, and Sally, his partner and caretaker.

<o> Rudy identifies a device implanted in Angie's skull: her father had apparently altered her nervous system to allow her to access the Cyberspace Matrix directly, without a "deck" (a computer with an interface directly into the user's brain), but she is not conscious of this.
<o> During their stay, Turner has a one-night stand with Sally, and then leaves for the Sprawl with Angie where he meets with Bobby's group in a shopping mall besieged by agents of Maas and Conroy.

<o> The only thing that saves his life is a sudden image of a girl made of light who interferes and unhooks him from the software just before he flatlines.

<o> As a result, he moved to Tokyo and began living with a widow and her daughter, with whom he fell in love.
<o> Later he convinced his childhood friend (known only as K), who was in dire straits, to move in with him.
<o> K confessed this love to Sensei, who was shocked, and later full of jealousy.

<o> Sensei, who had lost his faith in humanity after being cheated by his uncle, was horrified to find the same dark impulses lurking in his own heart, and felt a heavy guilt for the death of his friend.

<o> In the present, 1912, Sensei is prompted by the suicide (junshi) of General Nogi Maresuke (following the death of the Meiji Emperor) to take his own life, writing the letter to his only friend to explain his decision.
<o> From the age of thirteen, on the eve of the Great War, Millicent King keeps her journals in a series of exercise books.
<o> The diary records the dramas of everyday life in an ordinary English family touched by war, tragedy, and money troubles in the early decades of the century.
<o> From bohemian literary London to Rome in the twenties, her story moves on to social work and the build-up to another war, in which she drives ambulances through the bombed streets of London.
<o> She has proposals of marriage and secret lovers, ambition and optimism, but then her life is turned upside down once more by wartime deaths.
<o> The story is told in medias res and consists of three volumes: "The American Dream", "A Cold Day in Hell", and "A Bit Closer to Heaven".

column6: <o> When their sole Japanese guard dies, the women become part of a Malayan village community.
<o> They live and work there for three years, until the war ends and they are repatriated.
<o> Now a wealthy woman (at least on paper), Jean decides she wants to build a well for the village so that the women will not have to walk so far to collect water: "A gift by women, for women".
<o> Strachan arranges for her to travel to Malaya, where she goes back to the village and persuades the headman to allow her to build the well.
<o> While it is being built, she discovers that, by a strange chance, Joe Harman survived his punishment and returned to Australia.
<o> On her travels, she visits the town of Alice Springs, where Joe lived before the war, and is much impressed with the quality of life there.
<o> She then travels to the (fictional) primitive town of Willstown in the Queensland outback, where Joe has become manager of a cattle station.
<o> She soon discovers that the quality of life in "Alice" is an anomaly, and life for a woman in the outback is elsewhere very rugged.
<o> Meanwhile, Joe has met a pilot who helped repatriate the women, from whom he learns that Jean survived the war and that she was never married.
<o> He travels to London to find her, using money won in the Golden Casket lottery.
<o> He finds his way to Strachan's office, but is told that she has gone travelling in the Far East.

<o> Kira Argounova, the protagonist of the story, is the younger daughter of a bourgeois family.
<o> An independent spirit with a will to match, she rejects any attempt by her family or the nascent Soviet state to cast her into a mold.
<o> At the beginning of the story, Kira returns to Petrograd with her family, after a prolonged exile due to the assault of the Bolshevik revolutionaries.
<o> Kira's father had been the owner of a textile factory, which was seized and nationalized.
<o> Having given up all hopes of regaining their past possessions after the victories of the Red Army, the family returns to the city in search of livelihood.
<o> They find that their home has also been seized and converted to living quarters for several families.

<o> Innokentii Volodin, a diplomat, makes a telephone call he feels obliged by conscience to make, even though he knows he could be arrested.
<o> His call is taped and the NKVD seek to identify who has made the call.
<o> The sharashka prisoners, or zeks, work on technical projects to assist state security agencies and generally pander to Stalin's increasing paranoia.

<o> While most are aware of how much better off they are than "regular" gulag prisoners (some of them having come from gulags themselves), some are also conscious of the overwhelming moral dilemma of working to aid a system that is the cause of so much suffering.

<o> As Lev Rubin is given the task of identifying the voice in the recorded phone call, he examines printed spectrographs of the voice and compares them with recordings of Volodin and five other suspects.

column3: the helpers[SEP]contract usually results[SEP]pet shop claims
column6: <o> These points differ for each animal sold (although each animal's contract includes not showing it to anyone), and breaking this contract usually results in dire (and sometimes disturbing) consequences for the buyer, for which the pet shop claims no liability.
<o> Individual chapters of Pet Shop of Horrors are often based on these consequences, and are each written as a stand-alone story, usually introducing one or more new characters in each chapter.
<o> With the exception of the main characters and their families, it is rare for a character to carry over to a later chapter, providing the series with a very episodic nature.
<o> The detective Leon Orcot is used to tie the chapters together into an ongoing plot, usually in the form of a subplot within each chapter.
<o> Initially he suspects D of malicious criminal activity and using the pet shop as a front for drug trafficking.
<o> As the series progresses, he learns more about the pet shop and D himself, entering into a strange friendship of sorts with D as he works to uncover the truth.

<o> When the guests from Oz retire one night, Billina sleeps under the King's throne and overhears the King telling his chief steward how one can tell which of the ornaments were once people.
<o> She also learns that the King's magic powers reside in the Magic Belt that he wears.

<o> Billina was originally not going to be allowed to guess, but she so infuriates the Nome King by laying an egg under his throne (eggs are poison to Nomes) that he orders her to take her chances of being transformed by guessing.
<o> Since she knows the secret of the transformations, all of her guesses turn out to be right.

<o> The Scarecrow throws two of Billina's eggs, which he had luckily kept, into the Nome King's face.
<o> While the King is blinded by egg in his eyes, Dorothy takes his magic belt and uses its power to rout his army.

column3: the marshal of finland[SEP]great victory celebration[SEP]others finally return
column6: <o> After returning the royal family of Ev (the queen mother, five boys, and five girls) to their rightful forms and place, Ozma, Dorothy, and the others finally return to the country of Oz where a great victory celebration is held in the Emerald City's royal palace.
<o> Dorothy is officially made a Princess of Oz, Billina elects to remain in Oz, and Ozma uses the magic belt to send Dorothy to Australia where she is happily reunited with her Uncle Henry.
<o> A superluminal signal is sent to Earth, carrying with it an unusual energy blob that seems intent on capturing the Doctor.
<o> In the meantime, the homeworld of the Time Lords is under siege, with all the power sustaining it being drained through a black hole.
<o> Trapped and desperate, the Time Lords do the unthinkable and break the First Law of Time, allowing the Doctor to aid himself by summoning his two previous incarnations from the past.
<o> Initially summoning his previous incarnation, they find that the two Doctors do not get on and bicker constantly, and so attempt to retrieve his first self to keep them in order.

<o> Omega was a solar engineer who created the supernova that powers Time Lord civilization, and was thought to be killed in the explosion.
<o> In actuality, he had been transported to the antimatter universe, where his will and thought turned the formless matter into physicality.

<o> However, the Doctors discover that years of exposure to the corrosive effects of the black hole's singularity have destroyed Omega's physical body â€“ he is trapped forever.
<o> Driven over the edge by this discovery, Omega now demands that the Doctors share his exile.

column6: <o> The Virgin Missing Adventures novel The Empire of Glass states that the First Doctor is taken out of time between the stories The Time Meddler and Galaxy 4 but immediately before the novel.
<o> The Rani has opened a hole in time, allowing her access to the Doctor's timeline.
<o> She uses this to cycle through the Doctor's lives, causing him and his companions to jump back and forth between past and present incarnations.
<o> Her intention is to capture all of the Doctor's selves in a time loop, trapping him in London's East End; she has already captured the First and Second Doctor in the time hole.

<o> This causes the Fourth Doctor to send a message to his remaining selves, warning them of the Rani's plan: The Seventh Doctor and Ace are confused when the TARDIS lands in Greenwich, near the Cutty Sark, thanks to the Rani's attack on the TARDIS.

column6: <o> In the midst of an evacuation from the capital city, the Queen of Atlantis is caught by a strange, hypnotic blue light and lifted up into the "Heart of Atlantis", a powerful crystal protecting the city.
<o> The crystal consumes her and creates a dome barrier that protects the city's innermost district.
<o> She leaves behind her young daughter, Princess Kida, as the island sinks beneath the ocean.

column3: the life and adventures of remus[SEP]smithsonian institution
column6: <o> In 1914, Milo Thatch, a cartographer and linguist at the Smithsonian Institution who is marginalized for his research on Atlantis, believes that he has found The Shepherd's Journal, an ancient manuscript that contains directions to the lost island.

column3: la cage aux folles 3: the wedding[SEP]eccentric millionaire[SEP]museum board declines
column6: <o> After the museum board declines his proposal to search for the journal, a mysterious woman, Helga Sinclair, introduces Milo to Preston Whitmore, an eccentric millionaire.
<o> Whitmore has already funded a successful effort to retrieve the journal as repayment of a debt to Milo's grandfather, recruiting Milo to lead an expedition to Atlantis, as soon as he receives it.

column3: agni putrudu[SEP]journal recovery expedition[SEP]commander lyle rourke
column6: <o> The expedition departs with a team of specialists led by Commander Lyle Rourke, who also led the journal recovery expedition.

column6: <o> The crew includes Vinny Santorini, a demolitions expert; Mole MoliÃ¨re, a geologist; dr Joshua Sweet, a medical officer; Audrey Ramirez, a mechanic; mrs Wilhelmina Packard, a radio operator; and Cookie Farnsworth, a mess cook.
<o> During the journey, they are attacked by the monstrous Leviathan, a robotic lobster-like creature that guards Atlantis' entrance.
<o> The "Ulysses" is subsequently destroyed, but Milo, Rourke, and part of the crew escape by making their way to an underground cavern, described in the journal as the entrance to Atlantis.
<o> After traveling through a network of caves and a dormant volcano, the team reaches the borders of Atlantis.
<o> They are greeted by Kida who resembles a young woman and discover that the Atlantean language is the basis of many existing languages.

column6: <o> By swimming deep within the city's submerged ruins and translating underwater murals, Milo helps Kida uncover the nature of the Heart of Atlantis: it supplies the Atlanteans with power and longevity through the crystals worn around their necks.
<o> He is surprised this is not mentioned in the journal, but recalls that a page is missing.

column3: loren the amazon princess[SEP]crew betray milo
column6: <o> Rourke and the crew betray Milo, intending to bring the crystal to the surface and sell it.
<o> Rourke mortally wounds the King of Atlantis while trying to extract information about the crystal's location, but finds its location for himself hidden beneath the King's throne room.
<o> Rourke and the mercenaries lock Kida in a crate and prepare to leave the city.
<o> Knowing that when the crystal is gone the Atlanteans will die, Milo berates his friends for betraying their consciences, and ultimately convinces them to leave Rourke and remain in Atlantis.

column3: how the mail steamer went down in mid atlantic by a survivor[SEP]collective emotions

<o> He then reveals that the sinking of Atlantis was caused when he attempted to use it as a weapon of war.
<o> As he dies he gives his crystal to Milo, telling him to save Atlantis and Kida.

<o> On that same night, Julia is injured in a car accident, and Jack is offered a job by Xymos, because the project manager and a good friend of Jack, Ricky, is having software issues with the nanobots.
<o> He is shown a very complicated machine used to make the nanobots from bacteria.

column6: <o> As a result, hazardous elements such as the assemblers, the bacteria, and the nanobots were blown into the desert, evolving and eventually forming autonomous swarms.
<o> These swarms appear to be clouds of solar-powered and self-sufficient, reproducing and evolving (necroevolution) rapidly.
<o> The swarms exhibit predatory behavior, attacking and killing animals in the wild, using code that Jack himself worked on.
<o> Most alarmingly, the swarms seem to possess rudimentary intelligence, the ability to quickly learn and to innovate.

<o> Using a motorbike found in David's car, Jack manages to get himself and the semi-conscious Charley to the safety of the airlock before he falls unconscious again.

<o> At the plant, Jack, Mae and Bobby are enthusiastically greeted by Julia, who discharged herself from the hospital and was brought in by the chopper.

column6: <o> Julia's behavior seems to be extremely aberrant: She seems to pay heed to nothing other than trying to entice Jack and kissing him, even when Charley is found dead in the locked communications room with a swarm flying around him and the communication links cut.

column6: <o> Jack cannot understand how the swarm got inside the rigorously protected airtight building, why Charley would have disabled the facility's communications, or why Julia and Ricky seem to be coming up with various out-of-character ways of how he died.
<o> To Jack's horror, the video not only reveals that Julia and Ricky had an affair but also shows how Charley engaged in a vicious fight with Ricky and Vince.

<o> All of them end up in the communications room where Julia kisses a subdued Charley, injecting a stream of swarm into his mouth while Ricky sabotages the communication systems and they leave Charley to die from the swarm.
<o> Eventually, Jack and Mae realize that everyone in the facility except themselves have been infected by a symbiotic version of the nanobot swarms.

column3: melody cruise (film)[SEP]show aggressive predatory behavior[SEP]although evolved alongside
column6: <o> These nanobots, although evolved alongside the other swarms, do not show aggressive predatory behavior.

<o> Instead, while they seem to invigorate their hosts' physical statistics and their emotional perceptions, they slowly devour and take over their hosts to produce more nanobots, initially affecting their decisions and then controlling them, while allowing them to travel and contaminate others.

column3: partners (1932 film)[SEP]jack drink vials containing[SEP]producing coli bacteria
column6: <o> Mae and Jack drink vials containing a form of phage that kills the nanobot-producing coli bacteria.
<o> Jack then proceeds to take a sample of the phage and pour it into the sprinkler system and drench everyone with it.
<o> In the vicious struggle that ensues, Jack is captured and thrown into a magnetic chamber, with Ricky threatening him to reveal his plan or kill him by destroying the magnets.
<o> Jack feigns surrender when Julia walks in to interrogate him, but Jack then reactivates the magnetic chamber with Julia inside, remembering the incident with Amanda in the MRI.
<o> Julia's body disintegrates as a swarm is pulled away by the magnetic field to temporarily reveal the real Julia, who has slowly been consumed by the parasitic swarm.

<o> Before the swarm can repossess her body, Julia begs Jack to forgive her for putting him in danger, that she loves him, and tells him to stop the swarms and save their children from the same fate as they have been infected too.
<o> Motivated, Jack runs to the roof, evades the infected-team and finally manages to place the sample into the sprinkler system.
<o> In order to prevent the sprinkler system from triggering, infected-Ricky disables the plant's safety network.
<o> However, this is exactly what Jack wants, as Mae has already allowed the phage into the assembly line, causing the phage to reproduce rapidly.
<o> The assembly line is rapidly overheating because of the no longer active safety system.

<o> The infected-team, who are now doomed either way, choose to re-activate the safety network and get drenched with the phage.

column6: <o> The Tin Woodman and the Scarecrow are regaling each other with tales at the Woodman's palace in the Winkie Country when a Gillikin boy named Woot wanders in.
<o> After he is fed and rested, Woot asks the Woodman how he came made of tin.
<o> He relates how the Wicked Witch of the East enchanted his axe and caused him to chop his body parts off limb by limb, because he was in love with her ward, Nimmie Amee.
<o> Each chopped limb was replaced by the tinsmith Ku-Klip with a counterpart made of tin.

column3: ciudad bendita[SEP]longer love nimmie amee[SEP]tin woodman felt
column6: <o> (Since Oz is a fairyland, no one can die, even when the parts of their body are separated from each other) Without a heart, the Tin Woodman felt he could no longer love Nimmie Amee and he left her.
<o> Dorothy and the Scarecrow found him after he had rusted in the forest (an event related in The Wonderful Wizard of Oz) and went with him to the Emerald City where the Wizard gave him a heart.

column3: the life of juanita castro[SEP]woot suggests
column6: <o> Woot suggests that the heart may have made him kind, but it did not make him loving, or he would have returned to Nimmie Amee.
<o> This shames the Tin Woodman and inspires him to journey to the Munchkin Country and find her.
<o> The Tin Woodman, the Scarecrow, and Woot journey into the Gillikin Country and encounter the inflatable Loons of Loonville, whom they escape by popping several of them.
<o> They descend into Yoop Valley, where the giantess mrs Yoop dwells, who transforms the travelers into animals for her amusement, just as she has already done to Polychrome, the Rainbow's Daughter.
<o> Woot steals a magic apron that opens doors and barriers at the wearer's request, enabling the four to escape.

column3: no blood no tears[SEP]narrowly avoids becoming
column6: <o> Woot, as a green monkey, narrowly avoids becoming a jaguar's meal by descending further into a den of subterranean dragons.
<o> After escaping that ordeal, Woot, the Tin Woodman as a tin owl, the Scarecrow as a straw-stuffed bear, and Polychrome as a canary turn south into the Munchkin Country.
<o> They arrive at the farm of Jinjur, who renews her acquaintance with them and sends to the Emerald City for help.
<o> Dorothy and Ozma arrive and Ozma easily restores the Scarecrow and the Tin Woodman to their rightful forms.
<o> However, Ozma discovers that the Green Monkey into which Woot is transformed has to be someone's form; it cannot be destroyed.

<o> The Tin Woodman, the Scarecrow, Woot, and Polychrome resume their quest and come upon the spot where the Tin Woodman had rusted and find another tin man there.
<o> After they oil his joints, he identifies himself as Captain Fy-ter, a soldier who courted Nimmie Amee after the Woodman had left her.
<o> The Wicked Witch of the East had made Fy-ter's sword do what the Woodman's axe had done—cut off his limbs, which Ku-Klip replaced with tin limbs.
<o> Both woodmen now seek the heart of Nimmie Amee, agreeing to let her choose between them.

<o> Ku-Klip reveals that he used Fy-ter's head and many body parts from each of them (which never decayed) to create his assistant Chopfyt.
<o> Chopfyt complained about missing an arm until Ku-Klip made him a tin one, and he departed for the east.

<o> The companions leave Ku-Klip and continue east themselves to find Nimmie Amee and find themselves crossing the Invisible Country, where a massive Hip-po-gy-raf helps them across in return for the Scarecrow's straw.

<o> Woot is allowed free rein to roam where he pleases, Captain Fy-ter is dispatched by Ozma to guard duty in the Gillikin Country, and the Tin Woodman and Scarecrow return to his palace in the Winkie Country where the story began.

<o> After several years, one of the messengers returns bringing a trio of elders from the distant island of Shikoku, where development is not a problem and the tanuki are still worshipped.

column3: maisie goes to reno[SEP]temporarily transforming[SEP]remaining tanuki stage[SEP]urbanized land back
column6: <o> When all else fails, in a last act of defiance, the remaining tanuki stage a grand illusion, temporarily transforming the urbanized land back into its pristine state to remind everyone of what has been lost.
<o> Finally, with their strength exhausted, the tanuki most trained in illusion follow the example of the kitsune: They blend into human society one by one, abandoning those who cannot transform.
<o> While the media appeal comes too late to stop the construction, the public responds sympathetically to the tanuki, pushing the developers to set aside some areas as parks.
<o> Some try to survive there, dodging traffic to rummage through human scraps for food, while others disperse farther out to the countryside to compete with the tanuki who are already there.
<o> In a touching coda, one day, Shoukichi, who also joined the human world, is coming home from work when he sees a non-transformed tanuki leaping into a gap in a wall.
<o> Shoukichi crawls into the gap and follows the path, which leads to a grassy clearing where some of his former companions are gathering.

column3: scabs (hell on wheels)[SEP]literary critical piece[SEP]century french writer
column6: <o> "Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote" is written in the form of a review or literary critical piece about Pierre Menard, a fictional 20th-century French writer.

<o> Borges' "review" describes Menard's efforts to go beyond a mere "translation" of Don Quixote by immersing himself so thoroughly in the work as to be able to actually "re-create" it, line for line, in the original 17th-century Spanish.
<o> Thus, Pierre Menard is often used to raise questions and discussion about the nature of authorship, appropriation, and interpretation.
<o> "Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote" is a form of literary criticism, but through the medium of fantasy, irony, and humor.

column3: scooby-doo! spooky games[SEP]complete randomness eventually reproduces[SEP]infinite monkey theorem
column6: <o> In a pattern analogous to the infinite monkey theorem, all texts are reproduced in a vast library only because complete randomness eventually reproduces all possible combinations of letters.
<o> Both stories deal with the difficulty of creating meaning or perhaps finding or determining meaning.
<o> In the case of Quixote, the meaning depends on reader-response and/or context of the work.
<o> In the case of The Library of Babel, meaning is hard to find as any coherent works are rare.
<o> However, any work with meaning is random and not the product of human action and therefore drained of meaning.
<o> In the case of Quixote the human action of writing and reading the work affect meaning.

<o> Unbeknown to him and his colleagues, there is a base on the planet of an enemy of the League of All Worlds - a young world named Faraday, which embarked on a career of interstellar war and conquest, and which chose this "primitive" world as the location of a secret base.

<o> Alexander, who has learned that his adoptive father (and his lover), Count Ludwig (Ferdy Mayne), also a crusader, had killed Alexander's Greek parents, is gleeful that Jakob himself is in love with the Count, whom he had met after the Count and Alexander had split after an argument.
<o> This allows Alexander to take revenge for the Count's infidelity by telling his beloved Jakob about the Count's recent demise by drowning in a river, watched by an unmoved Alexander.

<o> Finally, it is revealed in Jakob's confession that Jakob received the inspiration for the crusade not from God but from the Count, which means that the crusade must fail, since it is not by the will of God.
<o> However, the monk is unable to stop the children's progression and is left behind.

<o> Anthony Fremont is a three-year-old boy with near-godlike powers: he can transform other people or objects into anything he wishes, think new things into being, teleport himself and others where he wishes, read the minds of people and animals and even revive the dead.

<o> He may not be wholly human; hints in the story mention his "odd shadow" and "bright, wet, purple gaze", and the obstetrician at his birth was said to have "screamed and dropped him and tried to kill him".

column3: captains outrageous[SEP]nobody knows whether anthony transported peaksville somewhere
column6: <o> Nobody knows whether Anthony transported Peaksville somewhere or whether the rest of the world (or for that matter, the universe) was destroyed and only the town remains.
<o> There is no electricity, and the residents have to make their own things and grow their own food; the latter is somewhat difficult as Anthony changes the weather per his whims.

<o> Nobody is safe from Anthony, not even his own family, although they can sometimes influence him slightly; after a "smiling" suggestion from his father, Anthony sends the remains of his victims into the family cornfield, after he has finished with them.

<o> Kilgore Trout is the only one not affected by the apathy, and thus helps revive others by telling them, "You were sick, but now you're well, and there's work to do".

<o> When Atreyu announces that he is the hero Gmork has sought, the wolf laughs and succumbs to death.

<o> Pingaree is an island in the Nonestic Ocean that surrounds the fairy countries that encircle the Deadly Desert that surrounds the Land of Oz.

<o> Many years before this story begins, the armies of Regos and Coregos sought to invade Pingaree, but their advance was repelled by Pingaree's king with the help of three magic pearls given to him by the Mermaids.

column3: solo (2006 film)[SEP]white pearl provided words[SEP]king superhuman strength[SEP]pink pearl protected[SEP]blue pearl gave
column6: <o> The Blue Pearl gave the king superhuman strength, the Pink Pearl protected him from any form of harm, and the White Pearl provided words of wisdom that only he could hear.
<o> Buoyed by the Pearl's magic powers, the king of Pingaree led his people to victory and the invaders from Regos and Coregos drowned on the return trip.
<o> At the beginning of Rinkitink in Oz King Kitticut and Queen Garee, the son and daughter-in-law of the victorious king are introduced.

column6: <o> The next day, a royal visitor arrives at the island: King Rinkitink of Gilgad, a jovial and pleasantly plump fellow on royal holiday, who remains on the island as Kitticut's guest for several weeks.
<o> Rinkitink's companion, other than the rowers from Gilgad, is a surly goat named Bilbil who seems to be Rinkitink's opposite in attitude.

column3: the last day of august[SEP]coregos come
column6: <o> Invaders from Regos and Coregos come again to Pingaree and seize the king before he can grab the pearls.
<o> All of the buildings are torn down, and all of the people are carried into slavery.

<o> The only ones remaining on the island are Inga, who was able to inadvertently hide by climbing a tree, Rinkitink, who escaped his pursuers by falling into a well, and Bilbil the goat whom the invaders did not see any value of.
<o> Inga realizes the only way he will be able to free his family and people is with the help of the magic pearls, so he comes to the palace floor to retrieve them.
<o> To make sure the pearls are not lost, he hides one each in the toes of his shoes and carries the speaking White Pearl with him.
<o> The White Pearl guides him to a boat the following morning, which he, Bilbil, and Rinkitink begin to row toward the island of Regos.
<o> Regos and Coregos are respectively ruled by a wicked king and queen, King Gos and Queen Cor.
<o> These two ruthless tyrants see no reason they cannot capture and enslave Inga and his companions as they did the rest of Pingaree's inhabitants.
<o> However, none of King Gos of Regos' forces can lay a hand on Inga, Rinkitink, or Bilbil when they are touching each other due to the Pink Pearl's power.
<o> They stride into the royal palace with the strength conferred by the Blue Pearl and force Gos and his evil forces to flee the island to Coregos and then free the king's slaves.
<o> Inga and Rinkitink wake the next morning to find the Pink Pearl is gone â€“ it was in the shoe that Rinkitink carelessly threw at a howling cat the previous night.

<o> While they are out searching for the lost shoe, the royal maid cleans their room and, finding the other shoe with no mate, assumes it was discarded and disposes of it accordingly â€“ and with it, the blue pearl.

<o> At a complete loss, Inga tells Rinkitink about the power of the Pearls and, at the advice of the white pearl, attempts to bluff Gos and his wife, Queen Cor, into believing he still has the power of the Pearls.

column3: the past of mary holmes[SEP]cor uses diplomacy
column6: <o> Cor uses diplomacy and trickery to capture him and Rinkitink and bring them to serve her on Coregos.
<o> Nikobob, a poor woodchopper who resides on Regos, finds the discarded shoes (unaware that they contain the Blue and Pink Pearls) and plans to give them to his daughter Zella.
<o> While he has the shoes, however, he encounters the giant worm Choggenmugger and chops it into pieces â€“ something he couldn't do without the pearls.
<o> Zella is wearing the shoes with the pearls inside when she delivers honey to Queen Cor on Coregos, Inga recognizes the shoes, and he offers his new shoes to Zella in exchange for his old ones.
<o> Now with the Pearls in his possession, he defeats Cor and sends her fleeing to Regos with the captive Queen Garee.
<o> The captives from Pingaree and all the other places the invaders have been are freed and sent home â€“ except for Inga's parents.
<o> To consolidate the situation of Regos and Coregos, Inga offers to make Nikobob king of the islands, which he adamantly refuses.
<o> They learn from a palace guard that Gos and Cor took King Kitticut and Queen Garee to the underground caverns of the Nome King, and Inga, Rinkitink, and Bilbil set out after them.
<o> Although Kaliko is a kinder Nome King than the previous one, he proves to be a politician who "prefers to deal with the strong".

column6: <o> At one point, hominids become sapient, and go on to develop technology, including an evolving universal constructor machine that goes to Mars and multiplies, and in an act of global ecophagy consumes Mars by converting the planet into a mass of machinery that leaves the Solar system in search of new planets to assimilate.
<o> Human extinction (or the extinction of human culture) also occurs in the book, as well as the end of planet Earth and the rebirth of life on another planet.

<o> (The extinction-level event that causes the human extinction is, indirectly, an eruption of the Rabaul caldera, coupled with various actions of humans themselves, some of which are only vaguely referred to, but implied to be a form of genetic engineering which removed the ability to reproduce with non-engineered humans) Also to be found in Evolution are ponderous Romans, sapient dinosaurs, the last of the wild Neanderthals, a primate who witnesses the extinction of the dinosaurs, symbiotic primate-tree relationships, mole people, and primates who live on a Mars-like Earth.

<o> In the book's epilogue, it is implied that the replicator machines sent by humans to Mars have developed sentience and high technology, unknowingly advancing the late mankind's legacy in the Universe.

column3: the tombs (novel)[SEP]sacrificial literary types[SEP]gradually moves away
column6: <o> Although Arthur at first holds to high ideals (he values "literature" over journalism, sacrificial literary types over opportunists), he gradually moves away from them because he wants to be a somebody.
<o> After first compromising his work, and obsessed with the woman, he is seduced into thinking that he has a chance with her.
<o> He further believes he has a choice between being phased out without making his mark or being "one of them", one of the inner circle who inherits power along with Them.

<o> She accurately chooses him for his weaknesses: his sense of failure and impotence as a writer with a need for significance; his isolation and willingness to join society; his snobbery and openness to flattering attention.
<o> While her reasons for bringing Arthur into play are not clear at first, they are complex.
<o> For the authors, Arthur serves as an observer and an experiment at the hands of the Dimensionists, proving their effectiveness on an individual's psyche.
<o> The story is a Machiavellian labyrinth involving the British Government's tenuous support for a railway baron, a bid to annex Greenland, and a tilt at party leadership.

<o> Themes of unrealised potential, the cold-blooded manoeuvering, and the upward climb of the influential mystery woman, fictionalise the intricacies and interactions of class and power in Britain at the time.
<o> Two contrasting mindsets of society are delineated by generational values or lack of them and the changes they portend for the everyday people they effectively rule.

column6: <o> Zero and Burton examine an old blood sample of Zero's under a microscope and discover Miss HIV (Michael Callen), who points out that the original study that was used to label Patient Zero as the first person to bring HIV to North America did not prove any such thing, but instead helped prove that HIV was sexually transmitted, leading to the development of safer sex practices.
<o> Under this interpretation, Zero could be lauded as a hero for his candor in participating in that original study.
<o> As Burton ponders this, an unknown fluid squirts from the eye pieces of the microscope, drenching Zero and making him appear on video.
<o> He joyously declares his innocence on tape but the effect only lasts five minutes before he fades away again.

<o> Uncle Max is nearly eaten by hyenas Shenzi, Banzai and Ed due to Timon's day dreaming.
<o> This becomes the last straw for the colony, prompting Timon to leave to find a better life.
<o> He meets the mandrill, Rafiki, who advises him to find his place in the world via "Hakuna Matata" and to "look beyond what you see".
<o> Believing Pride Rock to be his paradise home, Timon ventures to the rock and encounters Pumbaa the Warthog on his way.

<o> The pair arrive at Pride Rock during the presentation of the new prince to the Pridelands' animals (to Timon's annoyance, believing the crowd to be a long line to claim Pride Rock as real estate).

column6: <o> In the winter of 180D, the Roman emperor Marcus Aurelius fights to keep Germanic barbarians from invading his northern territories on the Danube frontier (a war which in fact had been ongoing for over a decade, with no end in sight as of 180).
<o> His deputies are the Greek ex-slave Timonides, a closet Christian, and the stern and honest general Gaius Livius.

column3: i'll be going now[SEP]philosopher daughter lucilla
column6: <o> Livius has close connections with the imperial family, being the lover of Aurelius' philosopher daughter Lucilla and a friend of her brother Commodus.
<o> Nevertheless, he is amazed to hear that Aurelius wants to make him his heir.
<o> Despite his military obligations the emperor has egalitarian ideals, dreaming of a day when Rome grants equal rights to men of all nations.
<o> He knows that he will not live to achieve this end, and trusts Livius to do so more than his charismatic but brutal son.

<o> Before he can do so he is poisoned by Commodus' cronies, who hope to secure their own political future by putting their friend on the throne.

<o> Meanwhile, Livius' army scores an important victory on the frontier, capturing the German chieftain Ballomar and his aides.

<o> Timonides wins the Germans' trust by successfully undergoing an ordeal, having his hand thrust in a fire; with his help, Livius decides to put Aurelius' policy into effect despite disapproval from Commodus.
<o> Lucilla helps convince Livius to defy the emperor, since she loved her father as much as Commodus hates him.

<o> Commodus is furious, and sends Livius back to his frontier post in what is effectively a sentence of banishment.
<o> Lucilla is forced to go to Armenia, with whose king she shares a loveless political marriage.
<o> Commodus is compelled to recall Livius in order to put down a rebellion by Rome's eastern provinces.
<o> When he arrives at the site of the unrest, Livius is horrified to find that Lucilla is behind it.
<o> She tries to persuade him to join her in making a splinter state, free of her brother's influence, but he feels that Roman civilization will collapse if it is broken into pieces.

<o> Black Boy (American Hunger) is a memoir of Richard Wright's childhood and young adulthood.
<o> It is split into two sections, "Southern Night" (concerning his childhood in the south) and "The Horror and the Glory" (concerning his early adult years in Chicago).
<o> The book begins with a mischievous four-year-old Wright setting fire to his grandmother's house and continues in that vein.

<o> He quickly chafes against his surroundings, reading instead of playing with other children, and rejecting the church in favor of atheism at a young age.
<o> He feels more out of place as he grows older and comes in contact with the Jim Crow racism of the 1920s South.
<o> He finds it generally unjust and fights against whites' and other blacks' desire to squash his intellectual curiosity and potential.

column6: <o> The story itself begins, typically enough, with a murderâ€”the Park Lane Mystery, the seemingly motiveless killing of the Honourable Ronald Adair, son of the Earl of Maynooth, a colonial governor in Australia.
<o> The authorities, not to mention the man's family, are perplexed by the case; it seems that Adair had not an enemy in the world.
<o> He was in his sitting room, with a window open, working on accounts of some kind, as indicated by the papers and money found by police.
<o> Adair liked playing whist and regularly did so at several clubs, but never for great sums of money.
<o> It does, however, come out that he won as much as Â£420 in partnership with a Colonel Moran.
<o> Motive: The motive does not appear to be robbery as nothing has been stolen.
<o> The only other way out was the open window, and there was a 20-foot (about 6 m) drop below it onto a flower bed, which now shows no sign of being disturbed.
<o> The narrator, Doctor Watson, having retained an interest in crime from his previous association with Holmes, visits the crime scene.
<o> He sees a plainclothes detective there with police, and also runs into an elderly deformed book collector, knocking several of his books to the ground.
<o> However, that is not the last that Watson sees of him, for a short time later, the man comes to Watson's study to apologize for his earlier behaviour.

column3: always in my heart (film)[SEP]placate rising racial tensions[SEP]head coach job
column6: <o> But, in an attempt to placate rising racial tensions and the fact that all other high schools are "white" only, Boone is assigned the head coach job.
<o> At first, he refuses as he thinks it is extremely unfair to Yoast, but accepts when he sees what it means to the black community.
<o> Yoast is then offered an assistant coach's job by the school board and initially refuses, but reconsiders after the white players pledge to boycott the team if he does not participate.
<o> Dismayed at the prospect of the students losing their chances at scholarships, Yoast changes his mind and takes up the position of defensive coordinator under Boone.
<o> The black students have a meeting in the gymnasium in auditioning to play for the team until Boone arrives, but the meeting turns into a fiasco when Yoast and white students interrupt.
<o> On August 15, 1971, the players gather and journey to Gettysburg College, where their training camp takes place.

column6: <o> Subsequently, the Titans go through the season undefeated while battling racial prejudice, before slowly gaining support from the community.
